<div id="review_1904210791" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1904210791" />
    <a title="J.L.   Sutton" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3675162-j-l-sutton"><img alt="J.L.   Sutton" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1438142892p2/3675162.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1904210791?book_show_action=true">Feb 05, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J.L.   Sutton" class="user" itemprop="url" name="J.L.   Sutton" href="/user/show/3675162-j-l-sutton">J.L.   Sutton</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1904210791" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5958080122008563093"><b>“I am what time, circumstance, history, have made of me, certainly, but I am, also, much more than that. So are we all.”</b><br/><br/>Better known for works such as Go Tell It on the Mountain, James Baldwin&apos;s Notes of a Native Son (published 2 years later in 1955) is an important collection of essays which highlights issues Baldwin would continue to address. Subjects of his essays include his own home life, life in Harlem, the inequities of separate but equal treatment of blacks in 1940s and 50s America as we</span>
  <span id="freeText5958080122008563093" style="display:none"><b>“I am what time, circumstance, history, have made of me, certainly, but I am, also, much more than that. So are we all.”</b><br /><br />Better known for works such as Go Tell It on the Mountain, James Baldwin's Notes of a Native Son (published 2 years later in 1955) is an important collection of essays which highlights issues Baldwin would continue to address. Subjects of his essays include his own home life, life in Harlem, the inequities of separate but equal treatment of blacks in 1940s and 50s America as well as his own experiences in France after WWII. <br /> <br /><b>“I am what time, circumstance, history, have made of me, certainly, but I am, also, much more than that. So are we all.”</b><br /><br /> <b>“You can not describe anything without betraying your point of view, your aspirations, your fears, your hopes. Everything.” </b><br /><br />Baldwin's prose still resonates and is relevant today. I find myself wanting to read more and more Baldwin!</span>
